Is the artist situation truly unjustifiably bad or is this just Mike being Mike? I get it sucks wanting to art ... and having to focus on creating product to vendor... but isnt that how you make money? Shouldnt you as an euntrapenuer artist be doing that to begin with? Being paid to travel and attend an event would be a nice perk but I thought many who vendor do the same in other conventions?
the problem is what they see themselves vs what the grand prix sees them as
the artists see this as they should be treated as a selling point for the grand prix, which is fair considering they are being used as a selling point for the show
the TO's see them as vendors

I mean honestly, I'm not as gun ho as I think most of the mtg community is for the vendors. If I was the convention runner I'd be doing something similar if I could get away with it. You're selling your stuff at my convention. I'm allowing it because you help bring people to it. I'm missing something because I thought that's how these work
it is, but for many of these artist it isn't actually worth their time to go out unless they are compensated more
The opportunity cost alone is pretty big cuz that’s time they could spend working
exactly
Ah
for most artists going to events like these it's just a money sink, they're lucky to break even
I'd imagine the conventions would respond "get good" at selling their product at the booths then XD
You think theyll change policy over this?
This seems like Mike being Mike but "art is good" is such an easy thing to go along with that he can bully people
I don't see any artists who have lines at their booth boycotting
that's a fair point jason
I think it’s an issue but not to the scale it’s become by any means
One thing I think I understand now though is my past experiences with some artists >.>. I've gone to a few of these and some artists are AWESOME... and some have this buy or f off attitude
... needless to say I bought art from the awesome artists and gave nothing to the others. .
But least I get the attitude now

Some of the artists in the letter I had never heard of. Titus lunter and I think Randy Gallegos were the only ones I recognized. But like Jason said, Mark Tedin and RK Post weren’t signing that. Maybe it’s Privileged of me to think it’s the new folks who don’t have the credentials that are wanting the same treatment as Dan Scott or Noah Bradley, which if you’ve only been doing mtg art for 2 sets...
Also guys like Lyon and Argyle do shit that gets them paid at those things too, extra fancy sigs etc. Those two were making $1000 bucks an hour in Vegas
That isn’t to say artists don’t have gripes
Yup.
I think they should get treated better there but Ken Meyer Jr bored shit sig is never gonna get him well paid
But then Chris Rush didn’t make anything at Vegas last year so you know the system is flawed because he’s the biggest name out there!
(He said with heavy sarcasm)

I'm a wannabe artist, I'm trying to be compassionate about it... but on some level it sounds like people are having unrealistic expectations. If the more popular artists are making money... then you can clearly make money. You have to crawl through with the rest of society trying to break their way into a market. If they think it's not worth the effort.... fine... but I dont think the conventions are at fault
Itd be nice if they accommodate but they shouldnt be expected to

As always it’s somewhere in between…the artists can have some unrealistic expectations, but also companies love to perpetuate the ‘you’re an unpaid intern because you have to pay your dues’ story because it’s cheap.
The only reason 99% of companies don’t have a machine at the building exit that grabs you, flips you upside down and shakes the change out of your pockets is because it isn’t cost effective. Yet.
Boston Dynamics is working on it.
Companies love to give the ‘we’re doing you a favor’ spiel so you feel beholden when they take use your work to help them make money.

Or at least ones where the owner doesn’t know every employee by name. The minute they’re big enough to have faceless employees is the minute you get treated like a faceless employee. Magic-adjacent companies are no different.
